==== CRITICAL FINDING: PREBUILT CUDA BINARY INCOMPATIBLE ====
timestamp: 2026-02-12 04:34:00

The prebuilt CUDA binary (b7347) is NOT compatible with this system.
node-llama-cpp silently falls back to Vulkan (AMD iGPU).

Evidence:
  $ bun -e 'import{getLlama}from"node-llama-cpp";const l=await getLlama();console.log(l.gpu,l.buildType);await l.dispose()'
  [node-llama-cpp] The prebuilt binary for platform "linux" "x64" with CUDA support
  is not compatible with the current system, falling back to using Vulkan
  vulkan prebuilt

Vulkan VRAM state (AMD iGPU, NOT the RTX 3090 Ti):
  {"total":50699485184,"used":63713280,"free":50635771904}
  = 50.7 GB total (system RAM via Vulkan), 50.6 GB free

Impact:
  - ALL previous test runs were using Vulkan, not CUDA
  - Production `qmd embed` was ALSO using Vulkan since at least Feb 10 (last bun install)
  - The NVIDIA GPU VRAM pressure from the ballast was irrelevant — model loaded to iGPU/RAM
  - This explains why no crash was observed: CUDA was never used

Fix:
  Built CUDA from source by forcing gpu: "cuda" in getLlama():
  $ bun -e 'import{getLlama}from"node-llama-cpp";const l=await getLlama({gpu:"cuda"});...'
  [node-llama-cpp] Cloning llama.cpp ... Building from source ...
  gpu: cuda, build: localBuild, total: 23.56 GB (correct — RTX 3090 Ti)

After local CUDA build, even default getLlama() picks up CUDA (local build takes priority).
==== END CRITICAL FINDING ====

