==== SUMMARY ====

1. PREBUILT CUDA BINARY INCOMPATIBLE
   The prebuilt binary (b7347) silently falls back to Vulkan on this system.
   Production `qmd embed` has been running on Vulkan (AMD iGPU) since at
   least Feb 10. This means the original CUDA SIGABRT crash was with a
   PREVIOUS local CUDA build that no longer exists (lost during bun install).

2. CRASH DOES NOT REPRODUCE WITH FRESH CUDA BUILD
   After building CUDA from source (using the llama.cpp bundled with
   node-llama-cpp 3.14.5), the crash does not reproduce at any VRAM
   pressure level, even with zero padding.

3. AUTO ALGORITHM IMPROVED
   The freshly-built CUDA binary's auto algorithm correctly handles
   VRAM pressure:
   - Default padding (1 GB): falls to 0 layers at ≤1000 MiB free
   - Zero padding: gracefully reduces 25→24→23→14→0 as VRAM shrinks
   - At 356 MiB free + zero padding: chose 14 layers and succeeded

4. POSSIBLE EXPLANATIONS
   a) The llama.cpp source bundled with node-llama-cpp 3.14.5 contains
      fixes to the VRAM estimation/auto algorithm that weren't in the
      previously-compiled local build
   b) The previous local build was compiled against a different llama.cpp
      commit (possibly from an earlier node-llama-cpp version)
   c) CUDA toolkit 12.8 handles OOM differently than the version used
      for the previous build

5. PRODUCTION IMPACT
   Production qmd has been silently running on Vulkan (AMD iGPU/system RAM),
   not CUDA (NVIDIA GPU). This means:
   - Embedding performance was degraded (no GPU acceleration)
   - The SIGABRT crash was masked (Vulkan doesn't hit CUDA OOM)
   - The fresh CUDA local build will now be used by production
==== END SUMMARY ====
